          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>A <html:em><html:strong>quasi-inverse</html:strong></html:em> to a function <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f \colon  A \to  B]]></fr:tex> is a function <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[g \colon  B \to  A]]></fr:tex> equipped with homotopies <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\epsilon \colon  f \circ  g \sim  1_{B}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\eta \colon  g \circ  f \sim 1_{A}]]></fr:tex>, rendering <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[g]]></fr:tex> simultaneously a <fr:link href="/foreign/erct.jonmsterling.com/erct-000Y/" title="Section-retraction pair" uri="https://erct.jonmsterling.com/erct-000Y/" display-uri="https://erct.jonmsterling.com/erct-000Y" type="local">section</fr:link> and a <fr:link href="/foreign/erct.jonmsterling.com/erct-000Y/" title="Section-retraction pair" uri="https://erct.jonmsterling.com/erct-000Y/" display-uri="https://erct.jonmsterling.com/erct-000Y" type="local">retraction</fr:link> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
            <html:p>Although no coherence laws are assumed for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\eta ]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\epsilon ]]></fr:tex>, we shall refer to them respectively as the <html:em>unit</html:em> and <html:em>counit</html:em> of the quasi-inverse.</html:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree show-metadata="true" expanded="false" toc="false" numbered="false">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:authors>
